        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> Actually,... As far as the pet doing 50% of damage theory?.... no I don't believe it. I believe if he strikes the killing blow.. then yes he'll get 50% of the exp. Reason why I know this?.. I tested it out with dozens of mobs, some expected, and unexpected. And it all rings the same thing. Any time my pet struck the last hit to kill a mob, I got 50% of exp. But everytime <b>I</b> stuck the last blow to kill the mob, I got the full amount of exp. Here is my basic layout..</P><P>1. Clinging/Engualfing/Dooming Darkness, to pull the mob. <BR>2. Send pet to fight Mob.<BR>3. Cast every available DoT spell, perferably the strongest ones you've got.<BR>4. Fear the Mob. <BR>5. Rest, or chase the mob. Let your pet wail on it. Occasionally recast fear if needed. <BR>6. Keep a steady eye on the mob's health. Once the mob's health drops to 20% of health. Use the pet command "/pet back off" to pull your pet off of the mob. Usually by this time, the mob your fighting is already running from you, feared or not.(exception is the undead or insects)<BR>7. Cast, or melee the mob till it's dead. Make sure you are the one to kill the mob, and not your pet. </P><P>And there you go. Everytime I did this routine, Its worked like a charm and have raked in all the experience. I even shared this recipe with other necromancers who fought me on it. With the same theory that others have discussed here in this topic. And they all thanked me. Course I'm not sure if this was already known,... Not saying I invented it, but maybe revised the old Fear Kiting, or helped pass on some important details.</P><P>Daedra Le'Vile<BR>43 Necromancer of the Tribunal Server.</P><P></P><P>The Topaz Beauty<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
